final List<Map<String, String>> devotions2026 = [
  // JANUARY 1-31 (31 devotions)
  {'date': '2026-01-01', 'title': 'New Year, New Life in Christ', 'scripture': '2 Corinthians 5:17', 'body': 'Therefore, if anyone is in Christ, he is a new creation; old things have passed away; behold, all things have become new.\n\nSarah struggled with addiction for years. Every January, she\'d promise change; February brought failure. This year, she invited Jesus into her struggle. She joined a recovery group, prayed daily, found church community. Week by week, chains loosened. By spring, months had passed without temptation. Jesus made her new.\n\nThis verse teaches us that when we enter a relationship with Christ, transformation isn\'t just possible—it\'s guaranteed. The old patterns, habits, and identities don\'t improve; they\'re replaced. New life in Christ means literally becoming a new creation. Not reformed, not improved, but new. Whatever needs to change in you—addiction, bitterness, fear, shame—Christ\'s power can transform it completely.', 'thoughts': 'What needs to be made new in you? Christ\'s power is available today.', 'action': 'Write one area needing transformation. Place it where you\'ll see it daily.', 'confession': 'Lord, transform me. I cannot change myself. Make me new through Your power. Amen.', 'author': 'NLCC'},
  {'date': '2026-01-02', 'title': 'Love as Jesus Loved', 'scripture': 'John 13:34-35', 'body': 'A new command I give you: Love one another. As I have loved you, so you must love one another.\n\nMarcus was efficient but cold. When a colleague\'s child got sick, Marcus did something unusual—he served sacrificially. He brought meals, listened, showed up. Months later: "Why did you do this?" Marcus replied, "Because Jesus did this for me." That opened doors to profound ministry.\n\nJesus sets a standard for love that\'s impossible by human strength alone: love others as He loved us. How did Jesus love? Sacrificially. Without condition. Despite being wronged. He didn\'t love when it was convenient; He loved in the most inconvenient circumstances—laying down His life. This command isn\'t about warm feelings; it\'s about deliberate choice to serve others\' interests above your own. When people witness this kind of love, they see Jesus.', 'thoughts': 'How can you show sacrificial love today—not to be seen, but because you\'ve experienced Christ\'s love?', 'action': 'Do one act of service for someone difficult to love. Tell no one.', 'confession': 'Fill my heart with Your selfless love. Help me love completely, without reservation. Amen.', 'author': 'NLCC'},
  {'date': '2026-01-03', 'title': 'Faith That Moves Mountains', 'scripture': 'Matthew 21:22', 'body': 'Therefore I tell you, whatever you ask for in prayer, believe that you have received it, and it will be yours.\n\nA village\'s only well dried up. The church gathered—not in desperation but faith. They prayed believing. Two weeks later, drilling deeper revealed water at an unexpected level. The community witnessed God\'s power. Dozens came to faith. The believers learned: faith moves more than mountains—it moves God\'s heart.\n\nThis verse challenges our typical approach to prayer. We pray and then hope God will answer. Instead, Jesus teaches us to pray, believe we\'ve already received it, and then watch it manifest. This isn\'t positive thinking; it\'s trusting God\'s character absolutely. When you pray in alignment with God\'s will and nature, He responds. The mountain doesn\'t move because you\'ve convinced yourself it will; it moves because God is faithful to His word. What impossible situation are you facing? God specializes in the impossible.', 'thoughts': 'What "mountain" are you facing? God specializes in the impossible.', 'action': 'Write one major prayer. Pray it daily this week thanking God in advance.', 'confession': 'Give me bold faith. I believe—help my unbelief. Amen.', 'author': 'NLCC'},
  {'date': '2026-01-04', 'title': 'The Heart of Love', 'scripture': '1 Corinthians 13:4-7', 'body': 'Love is patient, love is kind. It does not envy, it does not boast, it is not proud. It does not dishonor others, it is not self-seeking, it is not easily angered, it keeps no record of wrongs. Love does not delight in evil but rejoices with the truth. It always protects, always trusts, always hopes, always perseveres.\n\nJennifer was harsh with her staff. Then her child got sick; she missed her own kids growing up. She started reading 1 Corinthians 13 daily. She transformed: patient with mistakes, kind in corrections, protective of her team. Her workplace culture shifted. People requested transfers to work under her.\n\nThis passage is the DNA of love. Nine positive traits and three negative prohibitions. Notice love isn\'t primarily about feelings; it\'s about choices and actions. It chooses patience when frustrated. It chooses kindness when annoyed. It chooses to protect, trust, hope, and persevere even when everything in you wants to give up. This is the love Christ demonstrated and calls us to reflect. Which trait challenges you most? That\'s your growth edge.', 'thoughts': 'Which trait in this passage do you struggle with most? How can you grow?', 'action': 'Pick one trait. Actively practice it in every interaction today.', 'confession': 'Help me be patient when frustrated, kind when annoyed, generous when scared. Transform me. Amen.', 'author': 'NLCC'},
  {'date': '2026-01-05', 'title': 'Trust and Obey', 'scripture': 'Proverbs 3:5-6', 'body': 'Trust in the LORD with all your heart and lean not on your own understanding; in all your ways submit to him, and he will make your paths straight.\n\nDavid had a perfect plan. Then God asked him to leave his job and start a ministry everyone thought would fail. Every logical part resisted. But he chose to trust. Twenty years later, that ministry had transformed thousands. David said, "I\'m so grateful God ignored my plan."\n\nThis proverb offers a formula: don\'t depend on your understanding (logic), trust completely in God (relationship), submit to Him (obedience), and He will direct your path (promised outcome). The challenge is that God\'s way often contradicts logic. Your understanding says play it safe; God says step out. Your logic says protect yourself; God says give. Your reasoning says impossible; God says trust Me. True trust means releasing your grip on certainty and following God even when the path makes no sense. What are you trying to control that God wants you to release?', 'thoughts': 'What are you trying to control that God wants you to release?', 'action': 'Identify one area where you\'re leaning on your understanding. Write what trusting God looks like.', 'confession': 'Forgive my stubborn independence. Guide my steps. I trust You. Amen.', 'author': 'NLCC'},
  {'date': '2026-01-06', 'title': 'Known and Loved', 'scripture': 'Psalm 139:1-2', 'body': 'You have searched me, LORD, and you know me. You know when I sit and when I rise; you perceive my thoughts from afar.\n\nEmma was the invisible middle child—ignored at home, unpopular at school. Then she discovered Psalm 139. God knew her completely and loved her deeply. That shifted everything. Her worth wasn\'t dependent on others\' recognition—God saw her and loved her.\n\nGod knows you completely. Not just your public persona but your private thoughts, hidden struggles, secret dreams, and shameful moments. He sees everything—and loves you anyway. This is radical grace. You don\'t have to perform, impress, or earn His attention. He\'s already searching you, studying you, knowing you intimately. In a world that ignores or judges, God is perfectly aware and completely accepting. Your worth isn\'t determined by performance, popularity, or productivity. It\'s grounded in being known and loved by the God who created you.', 'thoughts': 'You don\'t have to perform to be worthy. God knows and loves the real you.', 'action': 'Sit quietly 10 minutes meditating on being fully known and loved by God.', 'confession': 'Thank You for knowing the real me and loving me anyway. Help me find worth in Your love. Amen.', 'author': 'NLCC'},
  {'date': '2026-01-07', 'title': 'The Gift of Salvation', 'scripture': 'Romans 6:23', 'body': 'For the wages of sin is death, but the gift of God is eternal life in Christ Jesus our Lord.\n\nThomas worked endlessly to earn God\'s approval. He read Scripture more than anyone, served tirelessly, tithed generously. But fear haunted him—was it enough? Then he understood: salvation wasn\'t earned; it was a gift. A burden lifted. He could serve from joy, not fear.\n\nThis verse establishes a critical truth: sin has consequences (death), but God\'s response isn\'t proportional judgment—it\'s grace through a gift. You cannot earn salvation through works, obedience, or merit. If you could, it wouldn\'t be a gift; it would be a transaction. Salvation is a complete gift from God purchased by Christ\'s sacrifice, not by your performance. This radically changes how you serve. You don\'t serve to gain God\'s approval; you serve because you already have it. You don\'t work to earn love; you work because you\'re loved. Freedom from earning grace is the foundation of authentic Christian living.', 'thoughts': 'If salvation were based on what you deserved, what would you get? That\'s why it\'s called grace.', 'action': 'Write a thank-you note to Jesus for the gift of salvation.', 'confession': 'I cannot earn what You freely give. I receive Your grace with gratitude. Thank You. Amen.', 'author': 'NLCC'},
  {'date': '2026-01-08', 'title': 'Love Covers All', 'scripture': '1 Peter 4:8', 'body': 'Above all, love each other deeply, because love covers a multitude of sins.\n\nRachel and her sister lived in cold civility because of an old wound. Then their mother got sick. The wound seemed insignificant. Rachel chose to love—not to pretend the hurt never happened, but to let love be bigger. Over weeks caring for their mother, the relationship healed. Love didn\'t forget; it forgave.\n\nLove doesn\'t erase wrongs or pretend they didn\'t happen. Instead, it places wrongs in their proper perspective: smaller than the relationship itself. When you choose to love deeply despite past hurt, love "covers" the sin—not by ignoring it but by refusing to let it define the relationship. This is how God handles our sin. He doesn\'t pretend we haven\'t sinned; He covers it through Christ\'s sacrifice and continues loving us completely. Love that covers isn\'t naive; it\'s courageous. It requires choosing relationship over resentment, forgiveness over fault-finding, and hope over bitterness.', 'thoughts': 'Love doesn\'t mean pretending wrongs didn\'t happen. It means choosing to forgive and restore.', 'action': 'Reach out to someone you need to forgive. Work toward restoration.', 'confession': 'Forgive me for keeping score. Give me a loving heart that forgives as I\'ve been forgiven. Amen.', 'author': 'NLCC'},
  {'date': '2026-01-09', 'title': 'Faith Over Fear', 'scripture': '2 Timothy 1:7', 'body': 'For God has not given us a spirit of fear, but of power and of love and of a sound mind.\n\nMichael terrified of public speaking was asked to present to his entire company. Panic set in. Then he remembered: God gave him power, not fear. He prayed, prepared, trusted God\'s presence. His presentation wasn\'t perfect, but it was real. He discovered fear has no power when you rely on God\'s strength.\n\nFear is real, but it\'s not from God. This verse clarifies that the spirit of fear is separate from God\'s nature. Instead, God offers three alternatives: power (to face what scares you), love (to remember you\'re not alone), and a sound mind (clarity to think strategically rather than panic). Fear whispers "you can\'t." God whispers "I\'m with you." Fear magnifies obstacles. God\'s power minimizes them. Fear isolates. Love connects. Fear clouds thinking. A sound mind clarifies. When fear rises, remember its source isn\'t God. Identify which of the three alternatives you need most right now.', 'thoughts': 'Fear is real, but it\'s not bigger than God. He already has a plan.', 'action': 'Name one fear. Pray specifically about it. Ask God for power, love, and sound mind.', 'confession': 'I give You my fears. Replace them with Your power, love, and peace. Amen.', 'author': 'NLCC'},
  {'date': '2026-01-10', 'title': 'The Ultimate Sacrifice', 'scripture': 'John 3:16', 'body': 'For God so loved the world that he gave his one and only Son, that whoever believes in him shall not perish but have eternal life.\n\nJoel\'s daughter was diagnosed terminal. He was devastated. A pastor asked: "Did you know God watched His own Son die?" Joel suddenly understood: God wasn\'t distant from suffering. He had entered it. That didn\'t take away the pain, but gave it meaning.\n\nJohn 3:16 isn\'t primarily about escaping hell or gaining heaven. It\'s about love so massive it motivated sacrifice. God loved the world—messy, broken, rebellious, ungrateful—so much that He gave His most precious possession. This isn\'t transactional love ("if you obey, I\'ll love you"). It\'s covenantal love ("I love you so I give everything"). The sacrifice reveals the depth of love. God didn\'t remain distant from human suffering; He entered it fully. Jesus didn\'t just die; He died in agony, betrayed by those He loved. God understands your pain intimately. He\'s been there. This changes everything about how we face suffering and believe in a God who cares.', 'thoughts': 'John 3:16 isn\'t just about heaven. It\'s about God\'s infinite love demonstrated in ultimate sacrifice.', 'action': 'Meditate on God\'s sacrifice. What does it cost you to truly believe?', 'confession': 'Thank You for dying for me. I receive Your sacrifice with humility and gratitude. Transform my life. Amen.', 'author': 'NLCC'},
  {'date': '2026-01-11', 'title': 'Love Your Enemies', 'scripture': 'Matthew 5:44', 'body': 'But I tell you, love your enemies and pray for those who persecute you.\n\nGreg\'s business partner started a competing company and bad-mouthed him. Greg\'s instinct was revenge. Instead, he prayed for his enemy daily. Months later, the competitor faced trouble. Greg helped him. That act of radical love transformed not just the business, but the competitor\'s worldview. He came to faith.\n\nThis command defies human nature. Loving enemies contradicts survival instinct and justice. Yet Jesus presents it as the marker of His followers. Why? Because loving enemies reveals God\'s character most clearly. God loves His enemies—us. While we were sinners, hostile toward Him, rejecting Him—He loved us. Loving enemies isn\'t naive or weak; it\'s the strongest force on earth. It disarms hatred, breaks cycles of revenge, and opens hearts to transformation. Praying for enemies doesn\'t mean condoning their actions; it means refusing to be defined by their opposition. When you love enemies, you prove you\'re not controlled by them.', 'thoughts': 'Loving enemies defies human nature and reveals divine power. Who is your "enemy"?', 'action': 'Pray for someone who wronged you. Pray specifically for their good.', 'confession': 'Loving enemies is impossible without You. Give me supernatural love. Amen.', 'author': 'NLCC'},
  {'date': '2026-01-12', 'title': 'Faithful in All Things', 'scripture': 'Psalm 89:8', 'body': 'LORD God Almighty, who is like you? You, LORD, are mighty, and your faithfulness surrounds you.\n\nWhen everything fell apart—job, marriage, health—Lisa clung to one truth: God\'s faithfulness never fails. She couldn\'t control circumstances, but could trust God was faithful through them. Years later, she saw how God had been faithful in ways she couldn\'t have orchestrated.\n\nGod\'s faithfulness isn\'t a promise that nothing bad will happen. It\'s a promise that God will be faithful regardless of circumstances. His faithfulness surrounds Him—it\'s intrinsic to who He is. He doesn\'t choose to be faithful sometimes and unfaithful other times based on performance. His faithfulness is constant, absolute, and unchanging. When your circumstances are chaotic, God\'s character remains stable. When you\'re confused about His will, His faithfulness continues. When you make mistakes, His commitment doesn\'t waiver. This is the foundation of trust: not that life will be easy, but that God will be faithful through all of it.', 'thoughts': 'God\'s faithfulness isn\'t dependent on circumstances. It\'s absolute.', 'action': 'List ways God has been faithful to you. Review when doubt comes.', 'confession': 'Thank You for unwavering faithfulness. When I cannot see the path, I trust You walk it with me. Amen.', 'author': 'NLCC'},
  {'date': '2026-01-13', 'title': 'Bearing One Another\'s Burdens', 'scripture': 'Galatians 6:2', 'body': 'Carry each other\'s burdens, and in this way you will fulfill the law of Christ.\n\nWhen Tom lost his job, his church stepped in. They brought meals, offered encouragement, helped job search. What could have been devastating became a season of profound community. Tom not only found a better job but developed deep friendships. He learned bearing burdens reflects Christ\'s compassion.\n\nBearing each other\'s burdens isn\'t optional charity; it\'s essential Christian practice. When you refuse to carry someone\'s burden because it\'s inconvenient, you reject the law of Christ—which is love. This doesn\'t mean solving all problems for others or enabling dependence. It means showing up, offering practical help, and sharing the weight. Jesus bore our heaviest burden (sin and death). He calls us to follow His model. True community isn\'t superficial friendship; it\'s carrying real weight together. When you bear someone\'s burden, you fulfill the deepest calling of Christian faith.', 'thoughts': 'True love means sharing in the struggles of others. Who\'s carrying a heavy burden?', 'action': 'Reach out to someone carrying a burden. Offer specific help, not just sympathy.', 'confession': 'Give me a compassionate heart. Help me to see and share others\' burdens willingly. Amen.', 'author': 'NLCC'},
  {'date': '2026-01-31', 'title': 'Hope in Jesus', 'scripture': 'Colossians 1:27', 'body': 'Christ in you, the hope of glory.\n\nIn her darkest hour, Hope discovered she\'d lost all hope—except for one thing: Jesus. As she clung to Christ, she rediscovered that all her other hopes were fulfilled in Him. He became her treasure, purpose, reason to keep going.\n\nHope rooted in circumstances, people, or achievement will eventually disappoint. Circumstances change, people fail, achievements lose their shine. But hope rooted in Christ—His character, His resurrection, His victory—never disappoints. Christ in you means you\'re never hopeless because His victory is already accomplished. You\'re not hoping things will work out; you\'re confident they\'re already redeemed through Him. This hope isn\'t denial of current pain; it\'s confidence that current pain isn\'t the final word. Glory is coming. Redemption is secured. Victory is assured. This hope sustains you through any difficulty. What makes you hopeful today? Is it something that could disappoint you, or is it rooted in Christ?', 'thoughts': 'Christ in you is the hope of eternal glory. All your hopes are fulfilled in Him.', 'action': 'Thank Jesus for being your hope. List what you find in Him that no one else provides.', 'confession': 'You are my hope. When everything else fails, You remain. Thank You. Amen.', 'author': 'NLCC'},
